snippet.textDisplay:
Man. This song is so good, it really touched me; deadass started crying. I'm not one to comment but I feel the need to share this. Sorry for the rant.

It makes me feel determined, inspired, almost like an unstoppable force? It takes me back to the time I got out to do groceries one evening and I was taken back by the feeling of actually being there. My surroundings were actually in the same "plane" as me, I noticed how vibrant everything is, how detailed everything is, the trees, the houses, stuff felt... Idk, real?
I used to keep my head low, afraid to do anything in public. Like maybe throw a McDonald's apple bag, because I thought that if I did, everyone would judge me and think I was a weirdo . Every conversation, every laugh, would be directed at me, to ridicule. I was keeping tabs on people who hurt me, dedicating my time to endless conversations on skype; looking down my phone so I didn't have to look at people in the eye. It was so weird, actually feeling like you were a part of this world after so much time of just feeling like you were looking at a 240p interactive video or something.
I changed schools and found myself in a class where I wasn't bullied, and friends who shared the same interests as me. Never in a hundred years would I have thought I'd be talking about my pretty unpopular interests (in the standards of a spanish-speaking third world country) offline. Putting yourself out there can be hard, but there's always gonna be someone interested in getting to know you; you're so much more special than you think you are. You're not alone, so many billions in this planet have felt, feel, and will feel your pain, you're valid. Put your mental health first, try and get to know yourself so you can start improving and get help of proffesionals if you feel like you need it. The only thing you can control is yourself, so go kick the ass of your demons. Slowly but surely, you'll get there. The world is waiting for you and cheering you on.

snippet.textDisplay:
Easily one of the best songs Gorillaz has put out in a while, this feels so much like a return to form.

If the entire album (or project, idk what the right word is for Song Machine) is this good and has a decent assortment of experimental sounds, we may have another Demon Days and Plastic Beach on our hands. And if its not as experimental but still this consistently good, it'll definitely top The Now Now, which was already a really good pop album, and further cement this direction Gorillaz is going in.

Either way, Song Machine made a really good first impression with this song, and this music video's production value is simply amazing.
